00:01:48.909 --> 00:01:50.100
don't get too distracted.

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:56.229
While I was doing the work on the series,
I was in the Boise, Idaho, airport one day,

00:01:56.229 --> 00:02:05.119
coming back from the Idaho Intelligence Fusion
Center, which is a place where the Department

00:02:05.119 --> 00:02:11.030
of Homeland Security has funded intelligence
fusion centers in all the states and sometimes

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:19.030
more than one in each state, to begin putting
together the intelligence on counter-terrorism

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:21.010
or on terrorists.

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:25.231
And a lot of the places like Idaho don't really
have a lot of business in terrorism, so they

00:02:25.231 --> 00:02:28.980
have turned it into looking for other kind
of crimes.

00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:35.460
But anyway, I was in the airport and I saw
this elderly woman over near the security

00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:36.460
scanner.

00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:41.440
She was in a wheelchair and she was struggling
to get herself up out of the wheelchair and

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:46.870
gripping the sides of the scanner to go through
you know the security clearance thing, and

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:52.980
one of the guards, the TSA guards, was painfully
looking at her and you know said, "Oh, are

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:53.980
you ok?

00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:54.980
Are you in pain?"

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:56.840
And she said, "No, I'm ok, I'm ok."

00:02:56.840 --> 00:03:01.790
So I said I'll, I took my notebook out and
I went over there, I was already in my mindset

00:03:01.790 --> 00:03:07.280
was, you know, this world had gotten so big
and it's so imprecise still and what keeps

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:09.030
us safer and what doesn't keep us safer?

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:15.630
And it sort of struck me as ludicrous that
this turns out to be 78-year-old grandmother

00:03:15.630 --> 00:03:20.440
from Boise, Idaho, would have to get herself
out of her wheelchair and go through the security

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:22.420
scanner in order to make us safer.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:27.300
So I went over to her and asked her, you know,
"What do you think about this hassle?"

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:30.620
And she said, "Oh, I don't mind it at all.

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:33.450
You know I could be a terrorist.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:35.630
I could have explosives."

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:41.870
She, you know, wearing her bright white new
tennies and her flowered jacket, you know,

00:03:41.870 --> 00:03:42.870
she was very happy.

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:46.460
But then all of a sudden she got really serious
and she said, "You know last time I went through

00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:48.300
here they didn't even check."

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:51.170
And she opened her jacket and she said, "I
could've had a bomb."

00:03:51.170 --> 00:03:52.170
[laughter]

00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:56.060
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: I'm thinking, well, maybe.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:04:03.400
But the fact is no, you know no terrorist
has been found out through these sorts of

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:09.390
security scanners and no terrorist has ever
fit the profile of Joy Whiteman, her name

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:11.400
was, 78-year-old Joy Whiteman.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:20.190
So is that a real good, good use of our money,
or what this became to me was a kind of perfect

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:26.590
metaphor for how to begin the book and how
to begin a process of questioning what is

00:04:26.590 --> 00:04:32.510
it that we've done with, in the post-9/11
world, with all the money and with our own

00:04:32.510 --> 00:04:36.220
fear about terrorism, what is it that we created?

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:43.510
And Joy Whiteman, in her struggle to get through
sort of exemplified that for me.

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:50.630
So what we did in order to answer some of
those questions is that my co-author and I,

00:04:50.630 --> 00:04:55.410
Bill Arkin, [laughs] who would be just died
and gone to heaven to be here because he's,

00:04:55.410 --> 00:04:57.220
he's one of you people.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:02.400
[laughing] He and I separately had begun to
look at this world.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:06.540
I began to look because I was covering the
intelligence community and I'd written about

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:12.410
the CIA's black sites, its covert operations
and how it was disappearing people after 9/11

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:14.930
in order to interrogate them.

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:19.150
And I had seen and met a lot of people from
organizations that were entirely new that

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:24.830
I had never heard of before and separately
Bill, working out of his barn in Vermont,

00:05:24.830 --> 00:05:27.760
had been seeing the growth in a different
way.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:30.060
He's a, he's a documents guy.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:36.870
So he was collecting government contracts
for the intelligence world that you could

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:40.050
see, 'cause lots of it's classified.

00:05:40.050 --> 00:05:46.430
And, and making lists and creating his own
databases and cross-referencing things, so

00:05:46.430 --> 00:05:53.050
he was getting contracts, but he was also
getting more obscure contracts like the distribution

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:54.140
of electricity.

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:58.830
He got contracts for companies that would,
that would keep track of that for different

00:05:58.830 --> 00:06:03.570
government agencies, so that if he saw something
on Google Maps, if he got pointed in that

00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:08.030
direction through other research and he saw
something that he got, had a suspicion about

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:12.360
what it was, he would get the electricity
distribution of that county and he would find

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:17.990
that, oh, my God, there's like a huge amount
of energy being used at this place and then

00:06:17.990 --> 00:06:24.360
in one instance he actually discovered through
that that this was a National Security Agency

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:30.780
downlink for its, its surveillance overseas
and what have you.

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:37.310
And then he would go on those super-secret
websites like Monster.com

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:38.310
[laughter]

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:45.200
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: and type in, and you can do
this too now, if you want to, type in top

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:54.540
secret in its search engine and up came at
that time thousands of job descriptions for

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.320
people with top secret security clearances.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:03.460
But not only that, it would have the job description
and it would have, depending on what company

00:07:03.460 --> 00:07:07.520
it was, some hint of what they were doing.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:13.690
And then in many cases it had five or six
code names for programs that they wanted that

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:15.190
person to be familiar with.

00:07:15.190 --> 00:07:19.630
It didn't say what the code names meant, but
it said that there were code names.

00:07:19.630 --> 00:07:25.450
And he began then, of course, he's a self-described
obsessive-compulsive person.

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:28.169
Best kind you know to be a researcher.

00:07:28.169 --> 00:07:34.580
So he would make lists of the code names,
lists of the uses of electricity, lists of

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:42.320
contractors and contractees, and eventually
and he would begin to cross-reference all

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:45.710
of these and some of them began to make sense.

00:07:45.710 --> 00:07:50.949
And then he would go to this other super-secret
website called LinkedIn, not quite a website,

00:07:50.949 --> 00:07:56.070
but network, and find that there were people
who had security clearances who were not supposed

00:07:56.070 --> 00:08:02.190
to be telling anybody what they did but they
were on LinkedIn and their biographies not

00:08:02.190 --> 00:08:08.270
only told you what organizations they had
worked on but sometimes what code name programs

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:10.020
they were familiar with.

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:16.520
So for us that was a confirmation of, of these
sorts of things and in some cases the LinkedIn

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:24.480
bios confirmed some of the more secret organizations
that we'd discovered, because you know we'd

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:28.410
think well it's actually called Tosa, well
I don't know is that a real name or could

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:29.990
it be Tose?

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:33.779
And we would search LinkedIn and there would
be some guy there who said he had at one time

00:08:33.779 --> 00:08:39.950
headed Tosa for such and such an agency.

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:44.920
When we got together and we decided that we
wanted to try to get our arms around the world

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:51.540
that was created in the military and intelligence
worlds after 9/11 to respond to the terrorists'

00:08:51.540 --> 00:08:57.120
attacks, one of the things that we wanted
to do was to be able to show it to people.

00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:03.740
And he was gonna be the one that quantified
it, or tried to, and I was gonna be the one

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:11.420
to get inside of it, talk to people inside,
put the, the flesh on the skeleton that we

00:09:11.420 --> 00:09:14.240
were hoping to create with his data.

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:19.120
And one of the things we both had experiences
with was locating things.

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:23.860
I knew from my secret prisons experience that
everything, even if it's, if it's supposed

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:27.870
to be covert and never found, lives somewhere.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:32.730
So we said well we should try to get addresses
and geo locate everything we find.

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:38.100
And it was painstaking, but we did that.

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:43.870
And we created what we call an alternative
geography of the United States.

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:51.440
Once we could put all these dots on our map,
we created a map of the United States that

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:53.820
we used to do our further reporting.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.420
A version of the map is on our website.

00:09:56.420 --> 00:10:01.500
And the version that's on the website excludes
a lot of information that we did, a lot of

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:07.650
detail that we learned, in part for security
reasons that we, that we thought about all

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:09.140
along the way.

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:13.890
So we want to tell people all we can about
this world, including making it real for them

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:18.020
so they don't have to rely on me, you know,
saying that it exists.

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:21.960
At the same time we want to be conscious of
some of the security implications.

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:26.050
So we have a map that that shows you the alternative
geography.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:31.240
We also thought about it kind of like a genome
project that we were creating the DNA, we

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:36.150
were mapping the DNA of this secret world,
which was a fun way to think about it.

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:41.270
And then once we had the map and the addresses,
I should say that some of the addresses came

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:48.930
about because he would give me addresses to
go visit, but I would also find some of my

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:55.000
own and give 'em back to him and as we went
back and forth we found that, for instance,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:00.560
if I went out to one place that he had given
me, then I would scope the whole area out

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:05.860
and end up giving him more addresses that
he would put back in his, in his database

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:08.360
and then go through his searches.

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:14.790
Google was helpful when we had an address
already because actually that's a huge, that

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:17.440
was the way that it was hugely helpful.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:22.680
And also Google Maps was incredible because
we and we spent a lot of time on Google Maps

00:11:22.680 --> 00:11:29.130
trying to, you know, once you could figure
out what the security looked like around a

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:33.180
place that was hiding in plain sight , you
could find all sorts of things that would

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:38.560
help you confirm whether you should keep going
or not or whether this was a total mislead.

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:45.770
But I first started, so we had this map that
we, or the map was developing.

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:50.440
I went out, so one of the, one of the hard
parts was trying to get inside the world because

00:11:50.440 --> 00:11:54.650
of course we don't have clearances and we,
which would be a silly thing, because I'm

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:58.910
a reporter, I do the opposite of trying to
hide information, I'm always trying to share

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:01.930
it, in a responsible way.

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:08.020
So I convinced the Defense Intelligence Agency,
which is the largest of the intelligence agencies,

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:14.779
even though the CIA gets all the attention,
it's relatively small, to let me sit in on

00:12:14.779 --> 00:12:20.920
a class that they were teaching on how do
you keep a secret conference, a top-secret

00:12:20.920 --> 00:12:23.580
conference, how do you keep that information
from leaking out?

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:29.529
'Cause I, one of the things I wanted to do
was to, to show how onerous keeping secrets

00:12:29.529 --> 00:12:31.910
is for the government.

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:34.670
So they let me come to the class, and it is
onerous.

00:12:34.670 --> 00:12:39.050
I mean we did everything from, you know if
this were a secret meeting, figuring out you

00:12:39.050 --> 00:12:43.770
know where to station the guards, how to take
your papers away from you, how to definitely

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:47.520
not let you bring any electronics into the
meeting.

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:52.459
If you did have notes you wanted to keep,
how to send them to you a way, in a secure

00:12:52.459 --> 00:12:58.810
way through the, through snail mail, and they
use couriers to drop the things at the post

00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:05.490
office, you know, it's just on and on to reverse
engineer that is an amazing thing, which,

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:06.490
which I did also.

00:13:06.490 --> 00:13:10.790
But while we were there, I learned how to
set a zephyr lock, which is this electromagnetic

00:13:10.790 --> 00:13:18.290
locks that are used to guard offices where
top secret information is going on.

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:22.730
I drove up to this place I'd never seen before
behind the Baltimore-Washington Airport, a

00:13:22.730 --> 00:13:28.790
place that I have been many times, and I was
in this neighborhood that was really eerie.

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:35.770
It just had a, it wasn't, it wasn't, it was
subtly eerie, which is even more eerie in

00:13:35.770 --> 00:13:36.770
a way.

00:13:36.770 --> 00:13:42.070
[laughing] All the buildings look different,
you know, they, none of them had or few of

00:13:42.070 --> 00:13:46.690
them had signs like where you were or what
company it represented.

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:52.650
Most of 'em had were of the same kind of architecture
and they had the same types of window film

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:58.490
on it and they had numbers on it instead of,
you know instead of the logos.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:14:03.529
And so I started, I would keep my laptop in
the car with me and put it and open it up

00:14:03.529 --> 00:14:08.209
usually to Google Maps, so that when Bill
was giving me addresses, you know, I could

00:14:08.209 --> 00:14:12.480
find them on the map, but then here I am in
this place that looks so weird, and I'm driving

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:17.430
around and I'm giving him addresses and he's,
you know, he's looking at it from his barn

00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:21.810
in Vermont on the maps and giving me, you
know, oh go here, go there.

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:28.100
And what it, what it turned out to be was
I was sitting in what we later identified

00:14:28.100 --> 00:14:32.339
as or called the Capital of Top Secret America.

00:14:32.339 --> 00:14:39.080
Which is not in Washington D.C., it's actually
north of Washington in Fort Mead, which is

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:42.660
where the National Security Agency resides.

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:47.990
And the NSA is one of the largest intelligence
agencies.

00:14:47.990 --> 00:14:55.100
It is involved in surveillance, electronic
surveillance of every kind, mostly overseas,

00:14:55.100 --> 00:15:02.300
but increasingly also in the United States
with the proper authorities.

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:08.830
And so this thing that I had stumbled upon
was the densest part of Top Secret America.

00:15:08.830 --> 00:15:14.019
And it was not only these government buildings
that were there, but contractors that were

00:15:14.019 --> 00:15:15.019
there.

00:15:15.019 --> 00:15:21.279
And we learned later as we as this world woke
up to us as we could see what was all around

00:15:21.279 --> 00:15:28.330
us in a different way, that you had a clustering
effect throughout the country.

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:34.570
And the clusters would be clustered around
a government, a big government agency, but

00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:39.660
then sub-agencies would come and grow up near
the big agency, the ones that worked with

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:46.320
it and then companies would relocate and develop
around them too, because they were now the

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:52.480
growing contractor base, which we knew existed,
but we didn't know to what extent it existed

00:15:52.480 --> 00:15:56.190
and that was also what we were trying to document.

00:15:56.190 --> 00:16:04.399
So for this cluster that we're talking about
here at the National Security Agency, it was

00:16:04.399 --> 00:16:11.149
so visible if you turned down the right streets
and I found the right streets because as I

00:16:11.149 --> 00:16:18.570
exited from the freeway to get into this location,
I was, you know my reporter's antenna was

00:16:18.570 --> 00:16:25.269
really up, and, meaning I don't know what
I'm gonna find, I'm looking at everything

00:16:25.269 --> 00:16:31.510
trying to just you know have all my senses
aware and I see a lawn sign, you know the

00:16:31.510 --> 00:16:36.900
kind of lawn signs that you see that says
Townhouses $400,000 and up?

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:47.930
Only this lawn sign said, Joe's Café, Job
Fair, Cleared Personnel, TS/SCI, which means

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:56.240
top secret/secure compartmented information,
which is above top secret.

00:16:56.240 --> 00:17:02.269
And so I went to Joe's Café and it was like
this divey café like you see all over the

00:17:02.269 --> 00:17:09.079
place, but instead of posters for you know
the newest kind of coffee or whatever, it

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:15.939
had information, it had Lockheed Martin and
General Dynamics and Khaki and SAIC posters

00:17:15.939 --> 00:17:26.819
for job positions and the little coffee holder
didn't have like Google on it, it had you

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:33.980
know it had Carahsoft, which is a company
that does top secret work in the IT space

00:17:33.980 --> 00:17:36.740
for the government.

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:45.090
So when I got there I noticed that right across
the street there was a big business park.

00:17:45.090 --> 00:17:50.080
And so I drove around the business park and
it was a business park, turns out, of the

00:17:50.080 --> 00:17:52.539
biggest contractors in Top Secret America.

00:17:52.539 --> 00:17:56.630
I mean I didn't know that at the time, I was
just writing everything down.

