00:35:03.530 --> 00:35:11.140
that helped soldiers figure out whether the
neighborhood was filled with neighbors that

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:15.190
belonged there or insurgents that didn't belong
there.

00:35:15.190 --> 00:35:21.310
Things like biometric and standoff biometrics,
where you know they can fingerprint people

00:35:21.310 --> 00:35:28.520
from a, remotely from a distance so you don't
even know it's happening, or mobile fingerprint

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:33.280
scanners so that if you get stopped at a for
a traffic violation they can ask you to give

00:35:33.280 --> 00:35:35.590
you, give them your fingerprints.

00:35:35.590 --> 00:35:45.420
Or, what I think is more powerful and less
and less viewed as, well it's just more powerful

00:35:45.420 --> 00:35:51.640
and less known, is the, the databases that
are being created to fuse, to bring together

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:57.370
different types of information and to mine
that for nuggets that will point to abnormal

00:35:57.370 --> 00:36:01.270
patterns or that will pull out an individual.

00:36:01.270 --> 00:36:11.250
Part of the, one kind of database that's emerged
and is in the book is the FBI's Guardian Database

00:36:11.250 --> 00:36:19.720
and it's filled with, the DHS is undertaking
a they have these things called Suspicious

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:27.850
Activity Reports, SARs, and they want local
police but also citizens to fill them out

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:33.110
if they see something, if they see somebody
doing something that's suspicious, that could

00:36:33.110 --> 00:36:36.520
be an indicator of terrorism.

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:40.670
There's one, there's one county, I think it's
in Texas, which has actually developed an

00:36:40.670 --> 00:36:46.850
app, so that if you get the app and then you
see somebody who's suspicious you could write

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:51.650
out, you can fill it out right then and there
and click and mail it in to the Department

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:55.800
of Homeland Security of that state and they
can maybe act on it.

00:36:55.800 --> 00:37:00.490
There's a reference in the book to a family
who was Middle-Eastern looking and they were

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:08.590
taking a picture of a fireboat at in the Balboa
harbor and they are now in this, in the database

00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:13.850
because if you're driving a car that has your
registration on it it's easy for the police

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:16.190
to you know note that.

00:37:16.190 --> 00:37:22.640
But the databases also, they, it can accumulate
a lot of information about you if you have

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:23.720
no criminal record.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:30.070
If you do have a criminal record, it's gonna
have that in it for sure, but if you don't

00:37:30.070 --> 00:37:35.620
because of another trend, which is just the
trend in coll-, in companies collecting private

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:40.780
information on people which the government
can now buy, just like the Washington Post

00:37:40.780 --> 00:37:45.680
can buy it to help me do my reporting, but
the government can now buy a lot of the privacy

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:51.280
informa-, a lot of the private information
and without a warrant like it needed before

00:37:51.280 --> 00:37:57.200
without probable cause that maybe you had
actually, not maybe but they thought it was

00:37:57.200 --> 00:38:02.310
probable that you had done something wrong,
now they can fill their database and your

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:07.670
dossier with with some of this information
without getting a warrant.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:12.160
So the databases are growing and you know
once you have a database with a lot of cool

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:17.790
data, you're gonna figure out what, [chuckles]
how to, how to use it, you're gonna try to

00:38:17.790 --> 00:38:21.490
mine it in different ways, this is sort of
the, I think you know this better than I do,

00:38:21.490 --> 00:38:23.010
but kind of the nature of the beast.

00:38:23.010 --> 00:38:27.460
If you've got raw data sitting around why
not you know play with it?

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:31.450
Let's see, I think we got a, we have a couple
more photos.

00:38:31.450 --> 00:38:36.369
So there's another example of the kind of
technology that came from the battlefield.

00:38:36.369 --> 00:38:43.970
This is the automatic license plate reader
which allows police to drive by and their,

00:38:43.970 --> 00:38:50.950
their cameras will automatically import the
license plates around them, run the criminal

00:38:50.950 --> 00:38:56.920
checks, I was sitting in the car with this
guy who'd developed this for Memphis, and

00:38:56.920 --> 00:39:00.890
they could tell so many different things about
the driver of the vehicle.

00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:04.980
So if they had a warrant it would kind of
go 'boing', and they could pull them over

00:39:04.980 --> 00:39:10.690
and make them pay or send them to jail if
you had an outstanding warrant.

00:39:10.690 --> 00:39:16.520
If it was a, my favorite was convicted gangster,
that's what they called them.

00:39:16.520 --> 00:39:17.520
[laughter]

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:21.230
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: I wasn't quite sure what gangster
meant, but [laughing] and it would you know

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:24.240
go like 'rrrrrrrrrrrrrr'.

00:39:24.240 --> 00:39:32.170
And then of course they had convicted child
molester and gang member and drug dealer and

00:39:32.170 --> 00:39:34.530
all that.

00:39:34.530 --> 00:39:38.450
So really can do a lot with that kind of thing.

00:39:38.450 --> 00:39:42.480
Before I take your questions, let me just
get through a couple more photos and then

00:39:42.480 --> 00:39:43.870
we can open it up for questions.

00:39:43.870 --> 00:39:44.870
&gt;&gt;Nick: That's it.

00:39:44.870 --> 00:39:45.870
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: Ok.

00:39:45.870 --> 00:39:46.870
Oh, perfect timing.

00:39:46.870 --> 00:39:47.870
You had a question in the back.

00:39:47.870 --> 00:39:49.940
&gt;&gt;male #1: Yeah, actually I was just kind
of curious, it seems, um, um, obviously be

00:39:49.940 --> 00:39:56.430
guessing about how big the government's growing
and should they have all these tools?

00:39:56.430 --> 00:39:59.740
I'm wondering what your opinion is about,
is, is this too much?

00:39:59.740 --> 00:40:00.740
Is this--

00:40:00.740 --> 00:40:01.740
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: Ok.

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:05.800
The question was it seems like we're guessing
about how big it is but do we have an opinion

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:10.460
about whether the big, the, the largeness
is good and effective?

00:40:10.460 --> 00:40:12.360
I'm really not guessing.

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:19.900
I mean we, we, we wanted to put together,
we wanted to document this in a way that was

00:40:19.900 --> 00:40:21.390
evidence based.

00:40:21.390 --> 00:40:22.390
Yeah.

00:40:22.390 --> 00:40:28.900
So, and, yes, the book and I do have an opinion
on it, and it comes from people on the inside

00:40:28.900 --> 00:40:34.330
who were really helpful who were very discouraged
by what they were seeing.

00:40:34.330 --> 00:40:41.200
And so the bottom line is I think that we're
a lot safer than we were on 9/11, but it's

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:46.120
not because of this giant thing that we've
created that we call Top Secret America.

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:51.810
It is because there are organizations, they
tend to be relatively small, within this group

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:59.830
of organizations, that have done some amazing
work and just to tell you what they are, probably

00:40:59.830 --> 00:41:06.160
won't be any surprise, but domestically the
FBI's counter-terrorism agents, that's where

00:41:06.160 --> 00:41:09.900
terrorism, that's where potential terrorists
have been identified.

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:16.130
By people who understand what they're doing
and have been doing it for a long time.

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:22.280
Overseas the CIA analysts who ended up finding
the Bin Laden compound?

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:27.740
Those people, relatively small group, laser-focused
on their mission, have been doing it for a

00:41:27.740 --> 00:41:30.500
long time.

00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:36.840
The special operations troops that we write
a whole chapter about them, they're really

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:42.240
a secret army that is grown up after 9/11
and has maintained more secrecy around it

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:45.140
than even the CIA's paramilitary operations.

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:51.220
They, if, if what you want is a group of people
to go and capture and kill, find, capture

00:41:51.220 --> 00:41:57.070
and kill likely terrorists, they're the people
you want to do it because they do it very

00:41:57.070 --> 00:41:58.480
effectively.

00:41:58.480 --> 00:42:08.050
Their, their, their raids are about 50 percent
accurate according to sources inside, which

00:42:08.050 --> 00:42:13.900
doesn't sound that great, but it's better
than a lot of other military organizations

00:42:13.900 --> 00:42:15.640
and there's always a cost to them.

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:21.860
If they kill the wrong people there's huge
blow-back to those and there have been a lot

00:42:21.860 --> 00:42:24.750
of blow-back on these very secretive operations.

00:42:24.750 --> 00:42:31.080
So yes, I think we are safer, but not because
of this giant thing.

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:35.140
And in fact the giant thing is imploding on
itself.

00:42:35.140 --> 00:42:39.680
In part because it's so big and people with
inside don't even know, you know, what else

00:42:39.680 --> 00:42:40.680
is inside.

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:44.650
&gt;&gt;male #1: Also, what's your opinion of Wikileaks
and Julian Assange and do you have any thoughts

00:42:44.650 --> 00:42:45.650
about that?

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:48.940
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: So two different questions,
first of all.

00:42:48.940 --> 00:43:01.080
You know, I met Julian before all the hoopla
and I would say that I'm not a great fan personally

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:12.080
and I think that his, his, some of his anti-American
statements are, are not helpful and you know,

00:43:12.080 --> 00:43:14.380
whatever, wrong-headed.

00:43:14.380 --> 00:43:20.590
However, I think the revelations that have
come out of the Wikileaks and the idea that

00:43:20.590 --> 00:43:26.380
there is such an organization that at least
is an anti-secrecy organization should not

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:33.700
be discounted at all and that we, and that
those documents provided some of the most

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:38.580
interesting revelations about our own government
in a long time.

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:44.190
Do I think that you know he's damaged national
security like some government officials have

00:43:44.190 --> 00:43:46.770
claimed?

00:43:46.770 --> 00:43:49.770
We haven't seen that yet.

00:43:49.770 --> 00:43:51.040
It could be.

00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:53.760
He was very sloppy in the beginning.

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:59.740
I think he didn't even understand how outing
government documents could put lives at risk,

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:01.410
like the lives of sources.

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:07.280
I know some of the reporters who worked with
him on the first tranche of, of articles who

00:44:07.280 --> 00:44:13.150
did know, because they had worked in this
field for a long time, and, and one of them

00:44:13.150 --> 00:44:18.380
said, you know we took our baseball bats out
at the very end before publication to drill

00:44:18.380 --> 00:44:23.520
into him that you had to be responsible with
this information because there were things

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:29.190
that should not be public because it will
put people's lives at risk.

00:44:29.190 --> 00:44:35.240
So I think the in general the government's
overreacted tremendously to Wikileaks in an

00:44:35.240 --> 00:44:36.240
uh.

00:44:36.240 --> 00:44:41.400
But the other interesting thing about Wikileaks
which I write about in the book, is the government's

00:44:41.400 --> 00:44:46.930
done a counterintelligence assessment of this,
like how did it happen?

00:44:46.930 --> 00:44:48.180
How vulnerable are we?

00:44:48.180 --> 00:44:50.380
How vulnerable are our documents?

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:55.450
Because one of the things they quickly discovered
was that the State Department, where all these

00:44:55.450 --> 00:45:01.420
cables came from, you know they, they put
a lot out on their, on their secret network,

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:06.880
called SIPRNet and, and it's easy to access
or it was at the time.

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:11.940
I mean, it's easy, it was very easy to access
if you had that level of classification and

00:45:11.940 --> 00:45:14.620
it shouldn't have been as easy as it was.

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:17.010
And they did that because they have no clue
what they're doing.

00:45:17.010 --> 00:45:19.010
And that's what the the assessment found.

00:45:19.010 --> 00:45:23.080
The assessment found that government agencies
that are supposed to be keeping secrets don't

00:45:23.080 --> 00:45:30.150
have a clue, by and large, of how easy it
is for people to break in or to get access

00:45:30.150 --> 00:45:32.940
and not really need to have access.

00:45:32.940 --> 00:45:39.420
The, the conclusion of the book has this very
fun, I, fun in my perverted way, this, this

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:46.500
fun parallel universe of on the one hand the
government after 9/11 cracked down on public

00:45:46.500 --> 00:45:51.770
information, declared a war on terrorism once
it was declared a war you know everything

00:45:51.770 --> 00:45:54.400
was secret because it could aid the enemy.

00:45:54.400 --> 00:46:03.600
At the same time, technology marches on and
I, I go up and interview the, the guys at

00:46:03.600 --> 00:46:09.930
a company, a pretty small company called Traversa,
that works for private companies trying to

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:16.240
find their proprietary information that's
made its way out of the company's secured

00:46:16.240 --> 00:46:20.860
site for various reasons, usually because
employees bring their work home and usually

00:46:20.860 --> 00:46:26.580
because their kids have file share software
and then that's like opening your door to

00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:31.290
your house and there are all these people
that do nothing more than go into houses looking

00:46:31.290 --> 00:46:32.660
for interesting files.

00:46:32.660 --> 00:46:38.130
And so they've found what they call the tuna
in the, the dolphin in the tuna nets, they've

00:46:38.130 --> 00:46:43.040
found a lot of government classified information
out there because people working for the government

00:46:43.040 --> 00:46:46.400
have put it out there unknowingly.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:52.450
That's to say that while the government's
scurrying around trying to keep you from information

00:46:52.450 --> 00:46:57.830
that I at least think is in the public interest
to know, to know whether our government's

00:46:57.830 --> 00:47:05.920
on the right course or not, technology is
making that all obsolete in a, in a certain

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:07.460
ad hoc way.

00:47:07.460 --> 00:47:10.680
And the people who study this inside government
know it.

00:47:10.680 --> 00:47:16.070
They know that they are losing this battle
and that there's this involuntary transparency

00:47:16.070 --> 00:47:21.220
that's occurring that Wikileaks best, best
symbolizes.

00:47:21.220 --> 00:47:26.830
So even people whose job it is to keep out,
to keep information from falling into the

00:47:26.830 --> 00:47:33.610
wrong hands, now believe that there's no way
they can win in that situation and that the

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:41.270
only way to really, the only way to really
work with it is to declassify many government

00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:50.480
secrets and to reassess what secrecy means
and to keep secret only what really needs

00:47:50.480 --> 00:47:55.960
to be kept secret and to do it in a way that
you know you can maintain that secrecy, because

00:47:55.960 --> 00:48:04.320
as this project shows you, you know, it's,
it's hard to keep a secret these days.

00:48:04.320 --> 00:48:07.590
So with that I think this is a good point
to take more questions.

00:48:07.590 --> 00:48:08.590
Ok.

00:48:08.590 --> 00:48:09.590
Yeah.

00:48:09.590 --> 00:48:11.330
&gt;&gt;male #2: You haven't mentioned the left
or the right in terms of political responsibility,

00:48:11.330 --> 00:48:19.020
so I'm curious, like, how much of this came
under the Bush administration, granted that

00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:20.480
was closer to when 9/11 happened.

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:21.480
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: Yeah.

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:25.290
&gt;&gt;male #2: How much has been either added
on to that or reversed under Obama?

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:30.120
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: So it all grew up under, under
President Bush.

00:48:30.120 --> 00:48:35.790
All the, a lot of the, most of the agencies
that we write about, most of the legal interpretations

00:48:35.790 --> 00:48:41.130
that allowed organizations like the Special
Operations to, to do what they do and in that

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:42.720
certain way.

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:45.200
But most of it has been continued under Obama.

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:51.930
He came in talking about transparency, talking
about the rule of law and disbanding some

00:48:51.930 --> 00:48:55.380
of the more controversial things.

00:48:55.380 --> 00:49:01.700
By and large he's not done any of that and
he's taken the Bush blueprint for counter-terrorism

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:03.430
overseas and run with it.

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:09.830
He's increased the lethal drone strikes and
he has increased the number of organizations

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:16.950
that work in Top Secret America by allowing
those, by allowing the individual agencies

00:49:16.950 --> 00:49:23.080
to create more of them and by not stepping
back and assessing, you know, where are we

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:24.370
now?

00:49:24.370 --> 00:49:29.210
What is really the threat, which I think is
step number one, is to have the government

00:49:29.210 --> 00:49:31.950
speak more honestly with us about the threat.

00:49:31.950 --> 00:49:36.550
There are several hundred Al-Qaeda left because
those organizations I was talking to you about

00:49:36.550 --> 00:49:39.640
before were effective in killing them off.

00:49:39.640 --> 00:49:45.620
And, yes, there have been new affiliates that
have sprung up, but the more effective organizations

00:49:45.620 --> 00:49:52.440
within this world, they have a, a good read
on them and they're, you know, likely to defeat

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:53.820
them, too.

00:49:53.820 --> 00:50:00.220
So we don't have, but we aren't given the
opportunity to know much, still about what

00:50:00.220 --> 00:50:04.660
is the real threat so you can then say, ok,
if this is the threat, this is what it looks

00:50:04.660 --> 00:50:07.340
like, what are we willing to spend on that?

00:50:07.340 --> 00:50:15.500
It's the basic risk analysis and, and we're
not there yet in part because it's not politically,

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:20.520
it's a bad idea to bring it up if you're a
member, if you're an elected official, one

00:50:20.520 --> 00:50:25.990
side or the other is gonna call you soft on
terrorism and then if there's another plot

00:50:25.990 --> 00:50:33.110
or a plot that's un, you know, that's stopped
even, but if there's a smaller incident that

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:35.650
happens, you know, you'll be blamed.

00:50:35.650 --> 00:50:40.930
And so I think that even the public has to
take some responsibility for not engaging

00:50:40.930 --> 00:50:45.660
in an honest discussion of what all this costs,
what's it worth, what is the threat?

00:50:45.660 --> 00:50:51.100
Because we're part of the problem in that
every time something might happen, you know,

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:56.920
you can bet that the media for sure is gonna
say you know, "Who's at fault here?"

00:50:56.920 --> 00:51:01.490
And the answer, the solution to all of that
is more.

00:51:01.490 --> 00:51:08.400
More money, more agents, more contractors,
more analysis papers, more, more, more.

00:51:08.400 --> 00:51:13.280
[chuckles] And I'd argue that that's not the
right approach anymore.

00:51:13.280 --> 00:51:14.280
Right behind you.

00:51:14.280 --> 00:51:18.120
&gt;&gt;male #3: So you, you talk a lot about how
you took very, very necessary precautions

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:20.060
to avoid publishing anything that could be
damaging.

00:51:20.060 --> 00:51:21.060
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: Right.

00:51:21.060 --> 00:51:25.370
&gt;&gt;male #3: Was that, was that part of your
core philosophy originally or, or how much

00:51:25.370 --> 00:51:36.630
of that was affected by the last, the last
week in, the last week of August when David

00:51:36.630 --> 00:51:43.010
Leigh's book on Wikileaks published the encryption
key for all of the unredacted cables?

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:46.240
&gt;&gt;Dana Priest: Oh, what you just mentioned
came out long before, I mean came out after

00:51:46.240 --> 00:51:47.880
all these decisions were made.

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:56.000
No, it comes from my work on in the intelligence
and military world where I come across information

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:02.610
that's pretty sensitive sometimes and every
time that that happens we have an unofficial

00:52:02.610 --> 00:52:07.530
procedure in which we, you know I'll get to
the point of having finished a story that

00:52:07.530 --> 00:52:13.460
has that information in, I'll call the government
up, I'll tell them what I have, so that they,

00:52:13.460 --> 00:52:17.620
if they want to, they can make a case that
something shouldn't be published.

00:52:17.620 --> 00:52:21.830
But the decision is my editor's, or the editor
of the Washington Post.

00:52:21.830 --> 00:52:26.030
But we need to know what the concern is in
order to even make a decision about it.

00:52:26.030 --> 00:52:30.180
And sometimes you're, you have something that
you know is sensitive, but you might not know

00:52:30.180 --> 00:52:36.510
how sensitive, so the government engages in
a discussion with the paper over these issues

00:52:36.510 --> 00:52:40.270
and, but the paper makes the final decision.

00:52:40.270 --> 00:52:44.980
So in the secret sites, the black sites, the
editor, you know, which went all the way up

00:52:44.980 --> 00:52:49.940
to the President, and our editor decided that
we would, we would put all the story in the

